<div style="margin-left:50px;">
<a id="comment-5597"></a>
<div class="comment">
 <h3 class="title"><a href="node/646#comment-5597" class="active">The moon is a pizza</a></h3>
 <div class="content"><p ><i >When you erase enough details, any two things look the same.</i></p>
<p >Hmmm.  But it makes a big difference to the usefulness of this sameness exactly what details you erase and what you keep.  As I've said before, in a totally different context, not all abstractions are created equal.</p>
<p >I could say that you and a jacko'lantern are the same because you both have faces, but I would hope that this analogy tells me very little about you that is of interest.</p>
<p >CT, on the other hand, shows that the concept of compositional mappings (a very specific abstraction) has deep ramifications throughout mathematics.  </p>
<p >It isn't necessarily a shock that such abstractions exist for a discipline like mathematics, but it is far from the case that some other random abstraction could do just as well.</p></div>
 <div class="links">By <a href="user/4" title="View user profile.">Marc Hamann</a> at Mon, 2005-04-18 18:49 | <a href="user/login">login</a> or <a href="user/register">register</a> to post comments</div>
</div>
